sentence-detokenized: FOOTBALL - HAPPY WIN FOR JAPAN, SURPRISING DEFEAT FOR CHINA.
Japan began their Asia Cup title defence with a fortunate 2-1 win against Syria in a Group C match on Friday.
But in the second match of the group, luck deserted China, who surprisingly lost 2:0 to newcomers Uzbekistan.

China controlled most of the game and had several missed chances until the 78th minute, when Uzbek striker Igor Shkvirin took advantage of a misdirected shot by the defense and headed the ball over the advancing Chinese goalkeeper into the empty net.
Oleg Shatskikou made sure of the win in added time, hitting an unstoppable left-footed shot from just outside the box.
The former Soviet republic is taking part in an Asian Cup final for the first time.
Despite winning the Asian Games title two years ago, Uzbekistan is in the final as an underdog.
Two goals from defensive errors in the final six minutes allowed Japan to come back and take all three points from their first game against Syria.

Takuya Takagi scored the winning goal in the 88th minute, standing up and heading towards the Syrian goal a shot by Hiroshige Yanagimoto that goalkeeper Salem Bitar appeared to cover, but then allowed the player to slip into the net.
It was Syria's second costly mistake in four minutes.
In the 84th minute, defender Hassan Abbas rose to head a long ball into the penalty area but could only direct it into the top corner of Bitar's goal.
In the seventh minute, Nader Jokhadar gave Syria the lead with an accurate header.
Japan laid siege to the Syrian penalty area for most of the match, but rarely broke through the Syrian defense.
Japan coach Shu Kamo said, "The Syrian own goal was a lucky break for us.
The Syrians scored an early goal and then played defensively and with long balls, which made it difficult for us. '
Japan, which co-hosted the World Cup in 2002 and is ranked 20th in the world according to FIFA rankings, is favourite to reclaim the title here.
Hosts UAE play Kuwait and South Korea host Indonesia on Saturday in Group A matches.
The four teams are tied on points from one game each.

FOOTBALL - LATE GOALS GIVE JAPAN VICTORY OVER SYRIA.
Two goals in the last six minutes gave Japan's holders an unqualified 2-1 win over Syria in the Asia Cup on Friday.
Takuya Takagi scored the winning goal in the 88th minute of the Group C match after goalkeeper Salem Bitar spoiled his flawless performance by allowing the ball to slip under his body.
It was the second mistake by the Syrian defense in four minutes.
In the 84th minute, defender Hassan Abbas rose to head a long ball into the penalty area but could only direct it into the top corner of Bitar's goal.
Syria took the lead with its first serious attack in the seventh minute.
Nader Jokhadar headed the ball from the right side of the box past Ammar Awad into the top right corner of Kenichi Shimokawa's goal.
Japan then laid siege to the Syrian penalty area and got a goal in the 16th minute that was disallowed for offside.
A minute later, Bitar made a good double save - first deflecting Kazuyoshi Miura's header and then blocking Takagi's follow-up shot.
In the 37th minute, Bitar again saved well from Miura, deflecting his header after a corner.
Japan started the second half brightly, but Bitar denied them an equalizer when he dove to his right to save Naoki Soma's low shot in the 53rd minute.

FOOTBALL - THE BAN ON BLINKERS HAS BEEN LIFTED.
Dutch striker Reggie Blinker was suspended indefinitely by FIFA on Friday and was due to return for Sheffield Wednesday against Liverpool on Saturday.
Blinker missed his club's last two games after FIFA banned him from worldwide tournaments for appearing to have signed contracts with Wednesday and Udinese while playing for Feyenoord.
The FIFA Players' Status Committee, meeting in Barcelona, decided that although Udinese's document was valid in principle, it could not be legally defended.
The commission said that the Italian club broke the rules by not informing Feyenoord, with whom the player had a contract.
Blinker was fined 75,000 Swiss francs ($57,600) for failing to inform the English club of his previous commitment to Udinese.
FOOTBALL - LEEDS' BOWLER FINED FOR INVOLVEMENT IN FAST FOOD SCANDAL.
On Friday, Leeds England Under-21 striker Lee Bowyer was fined 4,500 pounds ($7,400) for throwing chairs at restaurant staff during a disturbance at a McDonald's fast food restaurant.
Bowyer, 19, who was filmed by security cameras, pleaded guilty to a charge of wounding before a court in London.
He has been fined and ordered to pay a total of £175 to two employees injured in the East London restaurant brawl in October.
Leeds has already fined Bowyer 4,000 pounds ($6,600) and warned him that a repeat of his criminal behavior could cost him his place in the team.
Bowyer, who moved to the Yorkshire club in August for 3.5 million pounds ($5.8 million), was expected to play against Middlesbrough on Saturday.

RUGBY UNION - A BIT OF A MISS CAMPESE FAREWELL.
Centre Jason Little will miss Australia's end-of-tour match against the Barbarians in Twickenham on Saturday.
Little opted not to risk aggravating the knee injury that robbed him of much of the Tour, and has been replaced by fellow Queenslander Daniel Herbert.
Owen Finnegan has recovered from the knock he received during the Test against Wales last weekend, and retains his place in the back row ahead of Daniel Manu.

The Wallabies are aiming for a 13th successive win to finish their European tour with a 100 per cent record, but they also want to turn on the style and give David Kempes a proper send-off in his final game in Australian colours.

The Wallabies currently have no plans to make a special presentation to the 34-year-old winger, but the packed house of 75,000 spectators will still gather in the hope of witnessing one last moment of magic.
Kempes will face a familiar foe in Barbarians captain Rob Andrew - the man who knocked Australia out of contention with the last-gasp goal in the World Cup quarter-final in Cape Town.
"Campo has huge popularity in this country and the crowd has liked him since he first played here in 1984," said Andrew, who is likely to make his last appearance at Twickenham.
During their tour, Australia won all four Tests against Italy, Scotland, Ireland and Wales and scored 414 points at an average of almost 35 points per game.

League commitments have limited the Barbarians' selection options, but they still boast 13 international players, including England midfielder Tim Stimpson and recalled winger Tony Underwood, as well as All Black strikers Ian Jones and Norm Hewitt.

CRICKET - LARA HAS ANOTHER UNLUCKY DAY.
Australia gave Brian Lara another reason to be unhappy when they beat the West Indies by five wickets in the opening match of the limited-overs World Series on Friday.
Lara, who on Wednesday was punished for misconduct, was suspended for five days to extend his disappointing form on tour.
Australia, which led 2-0 in the five-Test series, overcame 172 West Indies with eight balls to spare to end a run of six successive one-day defeats.
All-rounder Greg Blewett steered his side to a comfortable victory with an unbeaten 57 in 90 balls to the delight of the 42,442 crowd.
Man of the Match Blewett came to the crease with the score at 70-2 and hit three fours during an untroubled passage of 129 minutes.
His crucial partnership with the fifth wicket and Stuart Law, who scored 21, added 71 off 85 balls.
Lara looked untouchable during his brief stint in the dugout before making a simple catch of Shane Warne at mid-wicket.
West Indies tour manager Clive Lloyd apologised for Lara's behaviour on Tuesday.
He (Lara) has told Australian coach Geoff Marsh that wicketkeeper Ian Healy is not welcome in the visitors' dressing room.
The crowd in Melbourne was clearly angered by the incident, loudly booing the West Indies vice-captain as he walked towards the middle.
It was left to fellow left-hander Shivnarine Chanderpaul to hold the innings with 54 points despite the setback of an injured groin.
Chanderpaul was forced to rely on a runner for most of his inning after getting hurt while returning to his spot to avoid a run.
Pakistan, which arrives in Australia later this month, is the other team competing in the World Series tournament.

CRICKET - LARA SUFFERS ANOTHER MISFORTUNE ON TOUR OF AUSTRALIA.

West Indies batsman Brian Lara suffered another blow during his tour of Australia, having already been punished for misbehaviour when he was dismissed cheaply in the first limited-overs match against Australia on Friday.
Lara, who received a stern rebuke from the management on his own tour after an angry outburst against Australian wicketkeeper Ian Healy, scored five runs to extend his poor form with the bat.
The West Indies vice-captain struggled for time during his 36-minute stint on the pitch before knocking the ball from medium pacer Tom Moody straight to Shane Warne at mid-wicket.
West Indies were 53 for two in 15 overs when rain stopped play at the Melbourne Cricket Ground after captain Courtney Walsh won the toss and elected to bat.
Lara's outburst three days ago seems to have set some of the Australian public against him.
As he headed for the door, he was greeted with boos from some of the audience.
On several occasions during his delivery, the crowd engaged in a series of obscene chants against him.

On Wednesday, tour manager Clive Lloyd apologised for the behaviour of Lara, who clashed with Australian coach Jeff Marsh in the opposition dressing room to protest his dismissal in Tuesday's second Test.
Lloyd did not say what form the disciplinary action would take.
Lara, who holds the record for the highest score in Test and first-class cricket, was unhappy with Healy's role in the incident and wondered if the ball had reached the Australia custodian.
Australia won the match at the Sydney Cricket Ground by 124 runs and led by two-nil in the five Tests after Lara failed to make both runs.
Lara has not yet scored a century since the West Indies arrived in Australia five weeks ago.
The West Indies and Australia team managements played down the incident, stressing that relations between the two countries were not affected.
Pakistan, who arrive next week, are the third team in the triangular World Series tournament.
